  "doc_id": "27630",
  "text": "The next operating scenario we consider is determined by the density of population of the geographical area supplied. A number of papers have already introduced this variable to test for its impact on the efficiency of water companies. Although most of them have focused on cost efficiency, their results seem to confirm the existence of economies of density, i.e., the higher the density of population the greater the level of efficiency [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] , Antonioli and Filippini, 2001 [CITATION_4] . Inconclusive evidence is also found by [CITATION_5] , while Tupper and Resende (2004) find empirical evidence supporting the existence of density economies in the provision of the service of water delivery, but not in the service of sewage collection. In our research, we find that technical efficiency is statistically greater for utilities supplying areas of high density of population than for companies serving sparsely populated areas.",
